04882nam a22007335i 9783110706833DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107068337 a10.1515/97831107068332doi  a(DE-B1597)551281  a(OCoLC)1334344137  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0720002bisacsh1 aWeiss, Lara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Walking Dead at Saqqara :bStrategies of Social and Religious Interaction in Practice /cLara Weiss. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (IX, 273 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligionsgeschichtliche Versuche und Vorarbeiten ,x0939-2580 ;v78  aHabilcMax Weber Kolleg Erfurtd2021.00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tChapter 1: Introduction -- tChapter 2: Representation -- tChapter 3: Offerings and other gifts at New Kingdom Saqqara -- tChapter 4: The veneration of gods and ancestors at Saqqara and beyond -- tChapter 5: Conclusions -- tAbbreviations and symbols -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aFunerary rituals and the cult of the dead are classics of research in religious studies, especially for ancient Egypt. Still, we know relatively little about how people interacted in daily life at the city of Memphis and its Saqqara necropolis in the late second millennium BCE. By focussing on lived ancient religion, we can see that the social and religious strategies employed by the individuals at Saqqara are not just means on the way to religious, post-mortem salvation, nor is their self-representation simply intended to manifest social status. On the contrary, the religious practices at Saqqara show in their complex spatiality a wide spectrum of options to configure sociality before and after one's own death. The analytical distinction between religion and other forms of human practices and sociality illuminates the range of cultural practices and how people selected, modified, or even avoided certain religious practices. As a result, pre-funerary, funerary and practices of the subsequent mortuary cults, in close connection with religious practices directed towards other ancestors and deities, allow the formation of imagined and functioning reminiscence clusters as central social groups at Saqqara, creating a heuristic model applicable also to other contexts.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by The Dutch Research Council (NWO)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAltägypten. 4aBrauchtum. 4aGedenken. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  aPractices.  aReligion.  aancient Egypt.  amemory.2 aThe Dutch Research Council (NWO)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022 Englishz978311099454408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022z9783110994537oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831107069320 cprintz978311066792940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110706833zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110706833zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110706833/original  a978-3-11-099389-9 EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  